\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 11. J. virginiana} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 1039 (1753). Dioecious pyramidal tree up to 30 m. Twigs 0·6-0·8 mm in diameter, very slender. Leaves all decussate; the juvenile 5-6 mm, often present on adult trees, long, spiny-pointed; adult leaves 0·5-1·5 mm, appressed but free at their acute or acuminate apices, often with a small gland on the back, entire and without a scarious border. Female cone 4-6 mm, ripening in the first year, ovoid, glaucous, brownish-violet when ripe; stalk erect or patent. Seeds 1 or 2, free.{\i  Planted for timber in parts of C. & S. Europe}. [Ga Hu It Rm.] ({\i North America}.)
